The fondness of Manilius for arithmetic and par- ticularly multiplicatiori sums must have struck every reader of the poem comically. See 11. 321 sqq„ III. 260, 279 sqq„ 423-617‚ IV. 445-497. Thirdly, the Ibis has at least one marked feature of Manilius' style, a double que attached to the two last words of a hexameter, e.g. 177 saxum uoluensque petensque¹.

Professor J. E. B. Mayor thinks Juvenal may have imitated Manilius in x. 175 constratum classibus isdem (mare) cf. Manil. I. 776 Persidos et uictor strarat qui classibus aequor, and in the declamatory passages on Hannibal, x. 155, 165, cf. Man. IV. 37 Quid refiram Cannas admotaque moenibus arma fl, and Xerxes cf. Iuv. x. 179 sqq. with Man. IV. 65, 66 Quid Xerxem, maius el ipso Nazffrogium pelago These indeed are doubtful. Woltjer however (de Manilio poeta, Groningen, p. 16) cites from a poem de Luna attributed in the MSS to a certain Claudius (Anth. Lat. Riese 72 3, Bahrens P. L. M. iii. 163) the following verse—

Luna decus mundi, magni pars maxima caeli, which is certainly from Manilius V. 12— Hinc uocat Orion, magni pars maxima caeli.

In the age of Constantine we can point to one writer who knew and used Manilius, the author of the Latin treatise on Astrology, Julius Firmicus. Scaliger has collected the passages in this work which are modelled on Manilius’ poem, and more recently Bechert has cited the most remarkable of them de emend. Manil. p. 18. Two of them bear traces of a very close imitation. Man. V. 61 sqq.
